      <title>Ranger Station Alex</title>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1108113/ranger-station-alex/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">d1c017e84868362bf7d22386432aed1d9f88037c</guid>
      <pubDate>Sun, 23 Jun 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Alexandra's plan is pretty simple: get a job as a forest ranger and fire lookout, start HRT, and then surprise everybody when she comes back home in six months. It's the best she can come up with, since her parents don't seem like they'd be onboard with the whole transitioning thing. But someone she meets on the job might just convince Alex to open up and let other people into her life...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Month 1&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Day 1&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Well, here it is, first day of the rest of my life. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I'm currently writing from the top of a lookout tower in Caddo National Park. I officially start as a park ranger/fire lookout today, but I'd been given a tour of the place about a week ago.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I had followed a gentleman named Donald  up the long flight of stairs to the top of the lookout tower. It's all just one big room, with windows, wrapping around it to give me a 360 degree view of my section of the park.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"This is Ranger Station Alpha." Donald said. He was a guy who could have been politely described as 'portly'. He had a large bushy gray mustache that he scratched as he spoke. "You'll be stationed up here for about six months. Bathroom is on the level just below us. Over there is a radio you can use to talk to central and the other rangers in their towers," he said while pointing at a radio set up on an old wooden table, "over there is your bed, and here is a footlocker you can store stuff in. There's an outlet over there you can plug stuff into; there's solar panels on the roof, that'll give ya enough juice for a laptop and a phone charger, and ya got satellite internet, but there won't be enough power for, like, a mini fridge, so keep that in mind." &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nodded as he spoke. I'd already read through the extensive paperwork the Park Service had made me sign before taking the job, so I knew about all these amenities.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I then followed Donald back down the stairs as he explained how food would be coming once a week, and I could message him through my phone if I wanted anything specific. He went through all my official duties; filing weather reports, keeping a lookout for fires, getting rid of rogue campers, stuff like that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Any questions?" He asked. I shook my head, and he said, "Well then, I look forward with working with you, mister."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I did my best to hide my discomfort and smiled. I hoped Donald didn't see how being seen as a man made me feel gross.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But luckily, I won't have to deal with that for long.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;See, I didn't write 'first day of the rest of my life' because I took this job.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I write that because I just took my first dose of estrogen just a few minutes ago.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Frankly I think I'm ingenious for coming up with this whole plan. I've saved up my money working fast food, stockpiled estrogen until I had enough for a year and some change, and then took this job as soon as it came up. I even inflated my resume a bit to make sure I got picked. No I can relax, enjoy nature, and transition in peace; Although I can imagine that Donald will get more confused about my appearance with every delivery he makes. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I'll admit there are some flaws with the plan. I can't check my levels for one thing; however, I'm going for monotherapy to avoid the side effects of anti-androgens, and I'm taking the estrogen subdermally, so my livers and kidneys shouldn't be at risk. I'm also not completely alone out here; there's a small town called Kelly about 30 minutes away. I'm allowed to go there one day a week as a break. My plan is to step up a PO Box there to get girl clothes from Amazon discretely.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It's convoluted, but it'll be worth it. I know it's basically a placebo right now, but I swear I can already feel my mind clearing up as the estrogen starts to do it's thing. I've wanted it for so long, and now I finally have it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Day 2&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh my god, is this what cis people feel like all the time?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I thought I was gonna have to take some time to like, ruminate on my gender and junk, but like, I don't really feel like that anymore. All the mental noise is just gone. I got too much time on my hands.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I'm doing my job, obviously. But I don't have to watch the forest 24/7. I'm getting really good at solitaire. Thinking of writing some stories or something. Or I could pull a Desert Solitaire and just sell this journal once I get out. It'd be a heck of a story.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh, I spoke to some of the other rangers. To my north is Ranger Station Beta, it's run by a girl named Cher. She's super nice. Our convo went something like this:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Hey, this is Alex, I'm the new ranger at Alpha. How are y'all today?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Oh-em-gee heeeeeeeeeeeey, nice to meet you! I'm Cher, I'm in Beta. Glad we got someone new in Alpha. What're your pronouns?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The question threw me for a loop. What should I--&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"She, her" I said without thinking. My voice barely sounded androgynous, how would she react?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yay, we have another girl out here!" Cher said. "This line of work can be a bit of a testosterone overload. Men will literaly just run off into the forest instead of going to therapy."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Sounds about right."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I swear, that Firewatch game gave way too many people the wrong idea about our jobs." Cher continued. "But hey, nice to finally meet ya."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yes, likewise." came a deep baritone voice over the radio.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Max, were you just listening in like a creep again?" Cher said, the exasperation in her voice obvious.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"It's an open frequency." Max said. His voice was monotone, like the worst teacher you had in school.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yeah, but you can at least let us know when you join in." Cher said. "Go work on your novel or something, the girls are talking."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Fine. Nice to meet you, Alex. I'm Max, I'm south of your position in Ranger Station Charlie. Talk to you later."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yeah, sure." I said. I wasn't sure what to make of the guy; he sounded a bit boring, to be honest.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Anyway, what brought you out to the woods, Alex?" Cher asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Oh, you know, just wanted to get away for a bit." I said. "See nature, get my zen on, help the environment, I'm sure you've heard it all before."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yeah, I have." Cher said. "Oop, hold on, I see some campers out where they're not supposed to be. Brb."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With that, Cher turned off her radio. Honestly, she seems like a gem. I'm glad to have another girl out here to talk to.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Another girl.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That felt good to write.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Day 5&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Went into town today to set up my PO box. Kelly looks Hallmark-esque; one long main street with brick storefronts. There's a lot of antique stores for some reason, some thrift stores, and of course the post office.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I went in and filled out all the paperwork relatively quickly. It was expensive, but it'll be worth it to get my new clothes. Plus it's not like USPS delivers to the middle of the woods.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But when I walked out of the post office this guy bumped into me. Right into my chest.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And I felt something.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I practically ran back to my car so I could look down my shirt.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Turns out my nipples are starting to puff up. They're like, constantly pointy now, and getting VERY sensitive. Not in a fun way, though. They're getting even more sore as I type this. I'm trying not to get my hopes up, but it's exciting that the changes are definitely happening.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Probably gonna need to get a bra, though. A padded one.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Day 12&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just tried on my first bra. Having a whole lot of emotions right now.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I'm crying. I don't really cry, but the tears are coming. It feels good, though. Cathartic. No one is around to say I'm not supposed to cry. I get to be a blubbering mess because I'm finally starting to like what I see in the mirror, and no one can give me any lip about it. I'm really a girl. I'm really doing this. Hallelujah.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Day 17&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Bought a skirt off Amazon. I've been wearing it around the station all day. Every once in a while I do a little spin. It feels really nice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Day 23&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Yep, definitely have breast buds.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh my god, I just stopped writing at some point, huh? I thought I would be documenting everything, be a bit obsessive about it. I guess I just..haven't felt the need to? Like, I'm on the hormones now, so I guess to don't feel the need to angst al over a journal like I used to. Huh.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Anyway, yeah, breast buds. Right now they're small, maybe a little larger than pea sized, but they're both sitting right under my nipples. Sometimes I'll be looking out over the forest and I'll just poke one to remind myself they're really there, and then I giggle a bit. God, I giggle now, that's crazy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh, I've been chatting with Cher a lot more. We kept it professional at first, but yesterday we got to talking casually mentioned she rewatched Clueless recently. I can't accurately transcribe the sound of pure shock and horror she let out when I said that I'd never seen it, but she insisted I bust open my laptop right then and there so we could get on Discord and have a movie night. Max had some opinions about this, but we just turned off our radios so we wouldn't have to deal with him. Not the most professional thing I've done, but it was an impulse thing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was a really fun night. I got to learn a bit more about Cher. Turns out she had a job as a graphic designer for this tech startup that was making waves last year, but then it turns out it was one big scam (as they increasingly seem to be these days) and the whole thing went bust. She had nothing to do with it, she just but together the ads, but it seems like it's been a stain on her resume lately. This job opened up and she decided to take it. She's been doing some small art pieces in the meantime, trying to get her mojo back. I feel really bad for her. Can't be easy to have your world turn upside down like that. She seems to be keeping a positive attitude, though.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh, and uh, she figured out I'm trans.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It happened while watching the movie, actually.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Man, I'm sorry I didn't watch this movie sooner." I said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yeah, I love helping new girls check out stuff they never got the chance to before." Cher said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My mind instantly locked in on the words &lt;em&gt;new girl. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;"&lt;/em&gt;Um, what do you mean, new girl?" I said, trying to sound like I was joking around.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I--oh, wait, was that offensive?" Cher said. "I have a trans cousin, and when she was transitioning we did this sort of thing all the time."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I, Uh..."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I wasn't sure if I should try and seem cis or what, but I figured if she'd clocked me it'd be weird to try and do that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Um, how did you figure it out?" I said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm sorry, I'm super super sorry, I just heard your voice and it sounded like my cousin when she was voice training so I asked for your pronouns to be sure I and I decided to just not say anything but I'm really sorry for clocking you I just--&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Cher, Cher, it's ok, I'm just...surprised, is all." I said. "I mean, I've been voice training, and it's not like you can see me, but I thought the radio just made me sound more femme or something."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Ok, I'm just glad I didn't upset you." Cher said. "Wanna go back to watching the movie?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yeah, let's." I said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So, yeah, turns out I got a whole ally just a radio call away. We've been talking about trying to find a way for us to go into town together so we can have a girl's day out (The thought of which fills me with pure undiluted gender euphoria), but it'll be tricky. Honestly, I thought I'd be able to just hide the whole trans thing, but the longer I'm on these hormones the more stupid that idea feels. I'm finally feeling confident for once in my life, and I want to act like it!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Woof, that was a lot to write. But hey, now I'm caught up. Hopefully nothing too wild happens for a while.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Day 30&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just spotted a small column of smoke out in my section of the forest. I checked through my binoculars and it looks like a small campsite. One tent and a small fire pit. I'm jotting down the info her before I head out on my ATV and check it out. I hope this doesn't turn into a whole thing. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
