      <title>Beating Hearts on the Burnished Dawn</title>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1105313/beating-hearts-on-the-burnished-dawn/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">2331602daa40c37c35245545408263d6e9e4f6d2</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 03 Jun 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Adventurers don’t retire in the world of Arbitas, they simply take nice vacations. It isn’t that they couldn’t retire, so much as the kind of person who craves adventuring also tends to chase that one legendary final job for one reason or another. As the first early mornings of summer draw over the vast valleys beneath Hornblende. With a deep breath, she raises her foot to the first step on the trail, heart skipping a beat as she whispers a quiet prayer to whatever listens to such things.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Liv wants to rest, relax, enjoy some of the wealth she’s built up… but that’s not why most people venture to Hornblende. Every year this sleepy mountain town becomes the host of a grand summer solstice festival called the burnished dawn - a morning in which comes once a year where the sun raises to its highest point in the sky line and causes the mountain ranges bordering Hornblende to cast a silvery light upon all its residents for a brief time. Those said to watch the burnished dawn together are also said to have their hearts bound in fate forever.  Liv will be one of many single eligible adventurers trying to scramble to find love in the summer before it happens.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Will our adventurer join in the festivities? Can she find someone to invite in the short two months she plans to take off? Will she give up her adventurous life in exchange for a more precious treasure? Where is the best place in town to get a slice of cake and a warm mug? Read and find out in… Beating Hearts on the Burnished Dawn&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: The first step is always the hardest.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;There she stood at the base of the mountain; the smooth carved stonework of the stairway leading to Hornblende ahead. She of course could’ve taken the traders’ path which was wide enough for carts, but this trail seemed symbolic to her. Her first steps towards Hornblende mirroring her first steps towards that dream of falling in love this summer. Every relationship up to now didn't seem to work out, but she was hopeful still despite herself. Her damn traitorous heart always seemed to stir when she imagined finding a partner to share her life with. It seemed silly… the kind of saccharine thing one of her romance novels might contain: ‘Take these steps as you take the steps to meet your one true love!’&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Liv steadied herself, took a deep breath, and placed a heavy steel-greaved boot on the first step. The world seemed to continue in spite of her slow and careful step: birds chirped, clouds drifted, and gentle breezes rolled by her cheeks. She could feel her face flush as she stood there embarrassed for a moment as she realized how excited she was. She took her time, but began the climb at a steady pace as she tried to banish the uncertainty from her heart. The trail was quickly swallowed by the mountain’s tree line and succumbed to shady woods. The carved stone gave way to dirt trails, only to occasionally pick back up in breaks in the forest floor. There were several cleared spots designed for people to stop and look back over the progress they had made up the mountain. The planes below grew further and further with each step, the people and features growing smaller and less comprehensible as they did.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She was startled  when she stumbled into one of these vistas which already housed two large orcish men locked in one another's’ embrace sitting at the top of the halfway point. They waved at her, paying little mind to anything other than their paramours as she sheepishly waved back with a polite smile. She had heard that this place was a lot more lax about its cultural stigmas, (which, truthfully had been a large part of why she was so curious about the Burnished Dawn festival), but she had no idea people would be so open about who they were. She caught herself staring at the curves of their musculature for a moment before shaking it off and trying to ignore the warm flush that once again graced her cheeks as she sought the trail again.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It felt like hours of rinse and repeat: climb a vast stretch of wooded mountain terrain, enter a clearing with a beautiful vista to peer out over the land, run into a couple or two that had already met at or come to Hornblende together. Her heart swelled with envy each time she passed another group enjoying the lookout positions (equally in envy as it was in admiration). She was determined to find&lt;em&gt; her&lt;/em&gt; person before the festival if it killed her. That’s why the metal armor didn’t bother her so much as she finally burst through the archway at the top of the mountain path and set both of her feet flat with a small stagger once the path ahead evened out horizontally. She was hellbent on this being the best two damn months of her romantic life, come dragons, gods, or anything in-between.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;In the valley between two enormous mountains there was a small city. &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;More of a large town really, but that was the least of her concerns. For the majority of the year, Hornblende was little more than a place to sightsee or trade for minerals that could only be obtained at such high up places. Few outside of dwarven smiths and jewelers' apprentices ever dared to climb the steep path, or brave the trade route that was carved into the side of a mountain which was barely wide enough for one cart (let alone its beasts of burden). But summer was a cherished time in this village, for with summer came the &lt;em&gt;Burnished Dawn &lt;/em&gt;festival!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The city was already bustling with people who were clearly travelers from many different lands and locales judging by their clothing and gear. Some seemed to be dressed in little at all, while others mulled about with entire camp setups on their snow jacketed backs. People of all different heritages and ancestries had already descended on the town en masse. There were some who came to peddle the wares they had created or found on their journeys, some who came simply to set up food and beverage stands, and more still who were here exclusively to participate in the eventual festival. Liv would fall into that last group, and though she was embarrassed to admit it, she had come here for one purpose: she wanted to find the kind of love she had read about in dusty borrowed tomes while she was traveling with her mercenary band.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Liv looked and acted like the type to take to sell-swording to pay the bills, but underneath that veneer secretly hid the fragile heart of a hopeless romantic. She loved taking art (paintings, sculptures, even a fine chair once-) as payment when divvying up spoils. She would often sing during her night watches to keep herself sharp and active when things drug on into the wee hours of the morning. She would always have some story of interest to relate to the others' in her various services at camps and warbands. So when she announced to the Ivory Eagles that she was going to take the summer season off to have an adventurer’s vacation, they were all surprised- even if they shouldn’t have been- when she announced her destination.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She rifled through her bag and looked for the ancient crumbling piece of sun-bleached parchment she had gotten as a letter years before. It was from her boon companion, a half-troll named Po. Soon it was in her grasp and as she uncrumpled it she made a mental note of the tavern’s name, “The Last Drop”. She smirked and shook her head, still remembering that night when she was training alongside him so many years ago where he pitched the idea. ‘I’m serious’, he had said, ‘Ye open an inn somewhere these adventurers flock, then ye get one really impressive drink or eat o' the menya, and &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;bam!&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Yer swimming in pieces fer the rest o’ yer days!’. She had chided him, but after his final outing with the eagles… Well she couldn’t really blame him for retiring early and opening that tavern.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Checking the town board at the center of the city for directions was an impossible feat of nimbly avoiding the larger folks, whilst simultaneously trying not to knock over those from smaller ancestries. Weaving in a crowd was usually hard enough without every third person being a mousefolk or drakken- but the various crates and goods being scurried to and fro in a frantic bid to make money before markets closed for the day certainly was not helping either. Once she’d made it to the three faced stone sculpture in the center of town she walked towards the side with her language inscribed on it. There were postings for small odd jobs, local performances and venues, and finally the town map. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Liv had barely gotten close enough to get a good glimpse when she was almost knocked down by a pink scaled drakken who wore leathers and accessories that matched the hue of their onyx black horns and sclera. Liv had heard of the half-dragons before, but had rarely seen one in person; again she caught herself staring in a hungry curiosity as she had the orcs from before.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;When the drakken was finished contemplating what they needed to see at the board, they noticed Liv’s attention and slowly rolled their eyes down into a shared gaze with the human. Her irises burned like orbs containing liquid fire, the sparks constantly in a state of flux that somehow retained a usual shape made of rusted gold. She felt compelled not to look away, as if some trance kept her bound in place until the drakken grinned slyly (at least she thought it was a grin, a bit hard to tell with the almost beak-like shape of drakken mouths), before revealing a very long, forked and &lt;em&gt;doubly pierced&lt;/em&gt; tongue that flicked with devious intent between them. As Liv tried her hardest to speak, the creature seemed to take great pleasure in the lack of any excuse she could muster to say as a way out. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You lost &lt;em&gt;little human? &lt;/em&gt;I could lead you around if you wanted."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There was an overwhelming confidence in her words. She was well aware of the effect it would have on the flustering woman who stood nearly two feet shorter. If Liv had been blushing before, surely her face was nothing short of the complexion a ripe tomato.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She didn’t know why she did it, but Liv quickly blurted an apology for bumping into them, bowed her head slightly, and left little but a small cloud of dust in her wake as she sped through the crowd towards The Last Drop.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Each step was met with a thunderous thump of her heart in tandem with the beating of her boots being slammed to the cobbled stone road to propel her away from the thing that stole her voice. But no matter how fast she moved, &lt;em&gt;that thing was bound to slither its way into her thoughts again.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When she arrived, she didn’t even catch any details of the tavern's facade&lt;/strong&gt;, save the worn and rusted metal sign that displayed a tipped and spilling tankard on it. She rushed her way inside without even stopping to let the door close behind her. She finally breathed a sigh of relief when the wooden door’s metal latch clicked into place after what felt like an eternity of waiting for it to close. Of course she had barely recovered for a moment before she saw a big goofy grin out of the corner of her eye. She turned to face him and his grin became a beaming smile of warmth and welcome.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Well sure as I be the devil’s bluest debtor, Lively has come to settle in me little inn.” &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He didn’t wait for her response before trying to hug her from across the bar that stood between them and she laughed as she wrapped her own arms around his tree trunk of a neck.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Po! I missed you so much! Also stop, you know I told you all to call me Liv!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He chuckled as he let her go gently and pulled back to the right side of his business. He was wearing clothes that were much nicer than she expected… when she had last seen him he barely knew to dress himself, yet now he wore something pleasant befitting a tavern owner in a tourist hotspot. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Too bad I dun have te listen to ya on account of me bein' retired from that band that calls ye Liv instead of Lively.” She pouted and he rolled his eyes before smiling again, “Fine, fine… What’ll it be this evening &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;miss&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; Liv?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Okay that’s a little too formal for my own flesh and blood to call me.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Funny, I don’t remember ye purchasin' none o’ my flesh at auction.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Oh that’s because I won it fair and square when I saved you from those dire bats.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Uh-huh…” he cocked an eyebrow, “I seem to recall that story going a bit different. But never mind that, blast it, stay on topic Liv: What the hell are you doing here in Hornblende?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Liv hesitated, telling the cheeky grinning Po everything he needed to know.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It took almost no time for her to settle into bed that evening.&lt;/strong&gt; She had insisted on paying, but Po had insisted on her staying for free if it could be helped seeing as, ‘ye got a world o’ fancy dates, bachelors, and maybe bachelorettes ahead o’ ye before the summer ends.’. She had always thought of Po as a little brother since her family first found him on the outskirts of their farm. A little crying troll boy who said he was left behind by his mom, couldn’t be more than 9 or 10 (despite being almost as tall as Liv’s father who was already considered great in stature for a grown man). Her parents almost turned him away, but she begged and cried and pleaded until they &lt;/span&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;finally&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt; relented and let him stay with them for a few days. Then a few months. Then a few years. And by the time Liv was ready to make her own way away from the farm, she had a formidable companion to travel with. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;The room she had come to settle in was the finest the inn had to offer, save Po’s own. It had a small fireplace on one wall, a small room for washing ones’ self using the latest gnomish aquamancy runes, and a large bed that could easily sleep two or three folks across from the fireplace. On the far wall from the door were two open windows with shutters that could be closed to keep out the heat of summer, or open to let in light and warm air as needed. And finally, the centerpiece of it all, a large comfy looking chair that had several pillows inside of it which Liv recognized as the same one she and Po had taken as payment after a night raid turned out to be a rather large waste of time.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She doffed her armor and threw her possessions down in a clattering heap beside the bed. Ever the weary one, she then placed a piton such that the door couldn’t be opened in the night. She didn’t truly believe that someone would be stupid enough to try to break into this tavern thanks to its owner, but old habits die hard and she was determined to die harder. She sat against the soft bed and her bones screamed with relief and exhaustion as she laid on something other than dirt for the first time in over a week of marching, hitching rides, and joining passing traders for a night.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She barely had time to think about what tomorrow might bring before she lost herself in a tangled dream of pink scales and a black horned punk someone &lt;span style="text-decoration:underline"&gt;&lt;em&gt;‘unlucky’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt; might bump into in this city.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
