      <title>Last Chance – A Sisters of Dorley Fanfiction</title>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1103594/last-chance--a-sisters-of-dorley-fanfiction/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">617e1f6a71b53570d3d12ee7cd9094f44bc81c95</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jul 2024 13:18:15 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Pim van Ulft moved to the United Kingdom in an attempt to reset his life, hoping that this would finally make him happy. But instead of finding happiness, his continued misery led him to the ultimate conclusion. Before he's able to finish the deed, he's saved by a girl, who brings him to a place where he can find the things he desires in life, at a cost.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He's going to have to face up to his deeply toxic masculinity and, eventually, become a woman.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: To Save a Life&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;h2&gt;2021, October 2&lt;br /&gt;Saturday&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Water rushed past his ears, drowning out all other sounds around him. The sensation reminds him of diving. He had long been a swimmer, ever since he was a child. He had won a few trophies doing it as a sport. That is now all in the past, a past that he has been trying to escape. A past that he intends to break with once and for all today. Four weeks after his twentieth birthday, his second year in the United Kingdom. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His final day in this world. It felt odd.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pim has many reasons to leave life behind him. Not that he would be leaving much behind, really. He has no friends, no real ones anyways. He has no family that cares about him, or at least, none he isn’t afraid to open up to, for fear of them looking into the abyss. His very own abyss. He has no money, no possessions he holds dear, no skills worth having. No future.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just another failure. Like his brothers. Drug addictions, alcoholism, unemployment, gambling and homelessness. That’s where they ended up, that’s the future that Mum insisted he would not end up if he went to university. If he just worked hard enough, if he used his talents, if he had discipline like she tried to ensure he had. If he was honest with her, with himself. She offered him all the support she could offer. Emotional support, advocacy, anything short of the finances their family had lacked all along.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Financial support that he was able to access, eventually, through the University. Saint Almsworth was a beautiful old town, a lovely place to live. Away from it all, from his old life. Apparently even another country didn’t make him feel like life was worth it. After looking through scholarship after scholarship, he was able to string together a range of scholarships from aristocratic kids who had died or disappeared here. The wealthy paying for his tuition and his rent, Pim worked to ensure he had something to eat and clothes to wear as well. Not that his money went to anything but cheap, unhealthy food about to give him some kind of cancer at 31 in addition to his copious consumption of alcohol.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Despite all the support, he failed. Failed, failed, failed. A supportive mother, many supportive, encouraging teachers and generous scholarships to a prestigious university like Saints. Rather than use what he was given, rather than take the advice his mother gave him, he isolated himself. Refused to attend most of his classes from the moment he was outside the influence of his mother. Barely do his homework, and pass with the most disappointing of grades he could get. Not that his mum knew what a third meant.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Not that she knew what had happened to him in all those years, all the mistakes he’s trying to erase alongside his existence. All the people he hurt. All the people who would be better off if he had never existed. Pim, just another mistake in a long range of mistakes. One she’d be better off without having to care about, worry about, think about, comprehend. She has enough sons to worry about in her life.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His mind raced back to primary school, back in the Netherlands. Cycling home from school, a few hundred metres from where he lived in his small town, and retreating back to his room. Crying, every single day. Being bullied, hit, called a girl. Unable to fight back. One of his elder brothers, 19 at the time, sat him down on his lap. He had to be more brave. Not let people do these things to him. For his own sake, because he deserved better than how he was being treated by the other kids.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pim internalised it, alright. He fought back. He hit them back. The first time, hurting them felt horrible. The tenth time, he didn’t care anymore. He’d get punished regardless. No matter if he fought back or not. He might as well try to actually hurt them, to scare them off. But rather than leave it at that, he used this new-found confidence in himself to hurt others. Be the bully himself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mum yelled at him when she learned. She threw things at him. Didn’t hurt him physically, thank god, but he hadn’t ever felt that scared before. He had hurt her by being a bad son.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pim couldn’t be a disappointing son. His mum had yelled a lot at his brothers too. He heard this in his room. It seemed to always be about money, about drugs. Police had entered the home at some points. Whilst he wasn’t allowed to see it, he realised that two of his brothers had been arrested at various points. And sometimes, when sneaking around in the evening, he could hear his Mum crying about it all. Hoping he wouldn’t make the mistakes his brothers had made. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And he did make those mistakes. For years. Hiding all of them from Mum. Hiding away from the world, in his room, as much as possible.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Luckily he found the internet. On youtube, watching various youtube channels around video games, one of the few escapes he could find. He had spent many thousands of hours watching youtube videos and playing games, deep into the night. And luckily, through games, he found his way to politics. To an actual understanding of the world. It was the same stuff that made the rest of his online acquaintances realise similar things about the world. The threat from the left and their authoritarian ideology, taking away everything they hold dear. He understands the need for a new renaissance, as has been proposed by Thierry Baudet, a politician and one of his personal heroes. That political movement is now left in ruins. Geert Wilders is old news. He’s been around for almost as long as Pim’s been alive. If only his namesake, Pim Fortuyn, had still been around. He would have changed that country for the better.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pim sighed and stepped out of the shower, drying himself with a towel. He looked into the mirror, and saw a disgusting person looking back at him. He never quite liked the way he looks; he’s an ugly boy. Very few women ever had interest in him, even as a friend. Especially the nerdy girls, the ones he would like to hang out with the most. They all thought he was, as he overheard, repulsive. Good news for them, he’ll no longer be there to be repulsive. Not after today.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His room is a mess. There are old, unwashed clothes everywhere. Piles of books, papers, homework that wasn’t mandatory to hand in. Empty bottles of beer and harder liquors. His bed is similarly messy, and he’s been informed by some that the smell from his room is ‘quite bad indeed’. It’s no longer his problem soon; they can have it, or burn it for all he cares. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He looks at his computer one last time. At the miniature tanks standing next them, all German. The boys online really liked German stuff, so he joined them, always making sure that his admiration for some of the World War II things didn’t grow into the beliefs of one of his brothers. He often said that this brother was ‘a bit of a nazi’. That kind of extremism was concerning to him, no better than the communists trying to destroy western civilisation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He put on his nicest blouse, ready to go into town. The plan was simple. Get over his nerves through alcohol. A lot of it. Because he really was quite nervous about what he was going to do. And then jump off the tallest building he can find. A quick death, and hopefully he’ll be too drunk to even realise what is really going on.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He looked at a mostly-emptied bottle of vodka in the corner of his room. Might as well start now. His hands slid across the cap, rotating it open, and he started to drink straight from the bottle. It felt like the vodka burned his throat away, his body rebelling against what he was doing, telling him to stop, yet he continued. Until there was not a single drop left within the bottle. Empty, as empty as he is himself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Time to go. There’s one last party to be had today, one last birthday to celebrate. And then, finally, it will all be over.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He won’t hurt anyone ever again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;***&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pim looks down at the ground below, hanging against the guardrail. Forty metres down. It suddenly feels much more real, scarier, like he will never be able to do it. The guardrail is around 25 centimetres away from the edge, and Pim climbs over, his hands desperately holding on to the bars. If he’s gonna fall, it will be intentional. Not an accident. He continues looking down for what feels like many minutes, his heart pounding, focusing on his breathing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It’s time. Time to let go. Literally. And just allow himself to fall to the end. Four seconds, four and a half? Just to reach the ground? And then it’ll be bang: no pain, just instantly gone. Dead. He hopes, at least. What if he does survive? Everyone will know about him, about his depression, his failures.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;His foot slips, and he’s barely able to hold his balance through his iron grip on the bars. He climbs back over the guardrail and sits down on the concrete. He cries as silently as he can and feels helpless, useless and especially hopeless.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He can’t even kill himself by letting go. All he had to do was let his hands go loose and let himself fall. He couldn’t even do that. Perhaps if he just didn't think about it. Did it as quickly as possible. No holding on. Just stand there and let his drunken lack of balance bring him down to the ground, to his death. Let’s do that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A soft, female hand pulls on his shoulder as he’s trying to climb over the guardrail again. The woman smiles at him, grabs his hand, pulling him away from the edge. She wants to… help him? Desperate, drunk, afraid, Pim tries to push her hard, to make her go away. So he can escape from whatever they want to do to him. But rather than push, he just finds himself falling on the concrete, the woman easily dodging him as if it was nothing. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He lost consciousness mere seconds later.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;2021, October 3&lt;br /&gt;Sunday&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;It could have been such a nice morning for Beatrice. A lovely sunday, the weather still warm, a nice cup of tea with Valérie. Over the past year they had made it a rule that their Sundays together would &lt;i&gt;not&lt;/i&gt; be interrupted. There are plenty of senior sponsors to bother for approval, and there are few things so urgent that it required her immediate attention. One time Bea even put on her most serious face, her most formal voice, and threatened to retroactively wash out any sponsor who dared disturb them on a Sunday. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A moment that was broken by Valérie laughing, removing the entirety of the atmosphere that had been so carefully built up.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Christine, as of today, is the inaugural breaker of this rule. Because of course it was Christine, the one who has broken all the rules of our organisation. A cardinal of operational security, and like most religious officials, the most likely to break the rules in the first place. And if she caused some major trouble, she better be ready to do her part in resolving it herself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Beatrice can hear a soft, hesitant, apologetic knock on her door. That must be Christine. Normally she would give Dorley Hall’s most  permission to enter. This time she’s opening the door herself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Christine was waiting in the hallway, impeccably dressed, donning just the right touches of make-up in the correct places to make her look like the kind of beautiful young woman Beatrice can be so proud of. Paige has taught her well! Really quite well. And ah, she’s blushing a little too? A bit anxious? Is that a touch of fear in her eyes?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh. Because she’s being stared at. Judged. Like she was before graduation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, forgive me Christine, I shouldn’t have been staring like that. Please come in. Do you want a cup of tea?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh, that would be lovely, thank you Aunt Bea.” The younger woman curtseys and smiles back at Beatrice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;By the book. Christine did something to be in real trouble.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After putting two cups on the table, she sits down across from Dorley Hall’s most troublesome employee. “So, Christine. What is so important that solving it requires breaking our newest most important rule?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Our problem is a &lt;i&gt;he&lt;/i&gt;, an additional he at that, someone I had to deposit in our basement late last night. The Dutch boy, Pim was his name. You probably remember him from the discussions, one of the boys rejected for lack of sponsors.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And you brought him here despite that lack of sponsors. What did he do to require inclusion in this year’s intake?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Christine sighed. “Steph and I went to a party yesterday, one organised by the faculty to get students of all years to intermingle, and we noticed him. Drinking heavily, he stared at us for a while, he stared at a lot of women present at the event. And at midnight, he left, and went to the top of one of the tallest buildings on campus. We stopped him from jumping off.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Beatrice continues for her. “And you brought him here.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I know. I know. It’s stupid. We should have brought him elsewhere.” Christine shakes her head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“This is the second boy you have dropped into our lap like this. And to Stephanie’s great credit, the last one proved to be quite the asset to our organisation. But there are rules for a reason.” Beatrice sighs. “And we are quite short on sponsors, as you already said.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We can let him go, if you so prefer.” The troublemaker readily suggests.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“So he can commit suicide next week? I doubt that was your intention in bringing him here.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We can bring him to a mental hospital–”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Beatrice interrupts her. “Someone we already deemed worthy of our programme, Christine? He’s going to be staying here.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Christine looks Beatrice in the eyes again, as if she knows exactly what the next words are going to be. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And you, Christine, are going to be his sponsor.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The newly-minted sponsor nods, having long-understood her fate before even entering the room, then smiles. “It seems no good deed goes unpunished around here.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Beatrice smiles back. “Not on a Sunday.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;***&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It feels like his head is going to burst open any moment now. Not that Pim would mind if it did. Not that anyone would mind if it did. If a chasm opened and there was a great disgusting scene in which–&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pim shudders. Such thoughts are too much, even for him. He wants to die: not imagine his death, or the pain and suffering inflicted upon himself in the process. The pain is what held him back all this time. The mere concept of pain makes every muscle in his body go tense. Maybe he should just open his eyes a little, walk a bit, try to do anything but lay in this bed and wallow in his misery. Something he tried to stop doing for fucking once. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;To destructive ends, but still. Some change in his life. Or well, not life.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Fuck. He just can’t get it out of his head. The idea, an idea he won’t be able to carry out in this stupid cell. He’s in police custody now, god knows what he did to deserve this, and he’s going to have to wait here for the police to be bothered to deal with him. And then go home, hopefully. Or to a mental hospital. Not that he would want to go back to his dorm, not today. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He opens his eyes and starts to pace around the concrete cell. Pacing is generous. He’s hobbling. His knee hurts so bad, something he didn’t notice until he started trying to walk. But what is a bit of pain? Push through it and…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Following a mighty stumble, one he was only barely able to balance himself out of, his hands pushing against the wall to stop him from hitting it at speed, Pim finally sat down again. The concrete is cold, and this green smock isn’t keeping him warm. Not that he deserves warmth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He was so stuck in his own world that he didn’t notice the woman standing on the other side of the glass wall, watching him in his cell. She knocks on the glass. His head tilts over. And she’s not a police officer, she’s… a normal woman. In a pretty dress, with a bit of make-up, looking at him with the same look of concern that the other woman had yesterday. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He looks a bit closer. It’s the same woman. Didn’t he see her at the party too? Or maybe he’s being so hungover that all women look the same to him now. His memory has often betrayed him lately. Since he started drinking.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Pim van Ulft, am I safe to come inside?” He had to laugh a little, nodding. Trying to sound serious when mispronouncing his name that badly isn’t going to work for him. But she’s bringing a tray with some food and something to drink, and he really needs that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She opens the door and brings everything inside, putting it down on the floor in front of Pim and sitting down on the side of the bed. “Please, feel free to eat. You had quite the nasty fall yesterday. And from what I could notice, you probably have a horrible hangover today.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He looks down at the floor, uncomfortable. Unable to speak. This woman sounds kind and gentle in a way he didn’t expect. Seems to be looking out for his well-being. And she probably has a whole lot of questions prepared for him, about what the hell he thought he was doing, but at least wants to give him the dignity of a meal before he has to admit his many severe mental health issues.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She continues looking at him, as he slowly eats his cereal bar. It’s awkward. Silent. He should look her in the eyes, he’s often been told to look people in the eyes, especially women. His eyes mostly stay at the floor however. Object permanence isn’t real, and if you don’t look at someone, they’re not real. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just him, his stupid cereal bar, a banana, and a bottle of water.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Don’t look at her. Don’t look at her, don’t look at the pretty lady and her–&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“My eyes are up here you know.” She says, strict.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He wants to be witty, say something like ‘of course they are, i’m not stupid’ or ‘I much prefer looking at these’, or– anything that he normally would say. But he feels dirty doing it to someone who seemingly saved his life. And he just freezes, unsure how he can even apologise for such a question. He looks down at the floor, and hears her footsteps slowly fade away and the glass door close.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He’s scared another sympathetic woman out of his life, and all he can do is sit on the floor, eat the stupid banana and drink the stupid bottle of water, and contemplate the end of his miserable little life some more. He’s fallen quite aways further down to rock bottom, but not in the way he wanted to.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
