      <title>Whiskeyed Away</title>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1099111/whiskeyed-away/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">d844154502cd879723764ac8d05b80e4ba11c649</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 29 Jun 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Living in the sunny city of San Diego, Erin Alvarez is on top of the world and thrilled to embark on her new college adventure. With her family right behind here, she sees a bright future ahead of her. Her mind brims with wholesome fantasies of forging lifelong friendships, yet she is surprised to meet her new roommate, Conner Reed, who doesn’t meet her expectations in the slightest.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Conner came to California for a simple reason: it wasn’t his hometown of Sparta, Tennessee. But when he meets Erin for the first time, it turns out there is a lot more to find than just an escape from home, especially when she starts uncovering his secret alter ego, Julia.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Whisked away from their old lives, the two find a new life with each other. Unfortunately for them, the past tends to entangle itself with the present. And when disaster strikes, suddenly the past is all that they have left.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;***&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The goal is to release at least 1 chapter a week, but this might change based off real life stuff. As I currently don't really have a big backlog. Writing is still mainly a hobby for me, so sometimes my day job will simply make me unable to put in the time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Also would love to connect with my readers, so please keep posting comments! If you want to have chat with me or other readers there is also a special writing discord I have made to talk with eachother at: https://discord.gg/WnHW84YxCQ&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I also have a free newsletter where you can find even more of my transfiction, and advanced chapters for this story! Sign up today: https://mailchi.mp/55990f6edc83/gwenington-story-corner&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1 – “Divine Alvarez Paella.”&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Violet’s arched eyebrows judge me from across the room. “You’re not taking that sad excuse for a horse with you to college.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“But—” I tilt my head, pout my lips, and make my eyes as big as possible. “Rainbow Sprinkle is my best friend.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She rolls her eyes. “Hello? I’m sitting right here?” Snatching the plushy horse with its mangled rainbow manes away from me, she holds it up in front of my face. The colorful collection of patches breaks up its silver cloth; I can remember the moment of thread and needle surgery for every single patch. “If your roommate sees you bring in this mangy mutt, your reputation will be ruined before classes have even started.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I lift my chin as I take back my nostalgia-filled plush. “I’m sure my future roommate will love Rainbow Sprinkle just as much as I do. You’re just jealous you don’t get to spend as many nights in my bed.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Violet smiles. “You wish. If only you could satisfy my unrelenting desire for masculine muscles.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I hear somebody’s looking for masculine muscles?” My brother David says as he appears under the doorpost. Below his curly hair and bushy eyebrows, a coy smile looks into the room. Wearing an oversized hoodie, it’s impossible to see if he has any ‘masculine muscles,’ but believe me, he doesn’t have any.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Vi is always looking for those. Sadly, there are none to be found in this house,” I shrug.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I don’t know Erin, you should see the kind of magazines Marco keeps hidden under his bed.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Need I remind you who originally owned those magazines?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;David shakes his head. “You’re a terrible influence on him.” He scrunches his nose. “It’s probably for the best that you’re leaving.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Rude.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“And wrong.” Violet backs me up. “Like you’re the one to talk to when he has boy troubles.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;David returns two playful finger guns and winks. “Good point.” Raising his eyebrows at Vi, he continues. “But in that case, I’ll just send him your way; you’re the expert on ‘boy troubles’ after all.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“What the heck is that supposed to mean?” She scowls.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“No, not like that.” David waves his hands in front of him. “Because you’re also into boys, not the other thing.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Violet sustains a judging glare in his direction. With her wide shoulders and bold eyebrows, it doesn’t take much for her to be intimidating.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“So—” I try to cut through the sudden tension. “Are you just here to be rude or— Did you have anything useful to say?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Yes, actually,” he exhales through his nose. “Dad says dinner’s ready in five minutes, so you should probably come down soon.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Tell him we’re on our way.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He nods and disappears down the hallway. I turn back toward Violet, who still looks a bit sore. Her legs are crossed, her back against my bed, and an auburn lock of hair cuts her face in half.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I throw Rainbow Sprinkle in her direction. “You know he didn’t mean it that way.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;While the colorful plushy lands in her lap, she sighs and rests the back of her head on top of my bed. Her eyes look upward to the ceiling. “I know.” She lifts her head off the bed and looks me in the eyes. “Still sucks though,” she says while pressing Rainbow Sprinkle close to her chest.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Yeah,” I stand up and hold out my hand to her. “But I’m sure some divine Alvarez Paella will cheer you right up.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;She chuckles and takes my hand. “Divine? Nobody but you crazies likes that stuff.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Just because I’m crazy doesn’t mean the rest of my family is.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;While Violet smooths out her dress and gets distracted by her phone, I look around my bedroom. If you didn’t know what was going on, you’d say a bomb had gone off in here. In the middle of the room, two giant suitcases stand open and spread out on the floor. Around them, there are at least a dozen piles of clothes. From tiny tops to jagged jeans and from scandalous skirts to cool coveralls, my entire wardrobe lies bare. Even though we will be driving down to campus tomorrow already, I still haven’t decided what to bring.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Not bothering to close the door behind me, I walk through the upstairs hallway and down the spiral staircase. The sweet saffron aromas have already taken hold of my nostrils, a smell that carries with it a thousand memories. Every time anything important is about to happen, my dad can’t help but bring out the rice to solidify the memory. Silly teenage breakups, grandma’s passing, even my high school graduation, all of it is marked with that one special meal.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I walk into the kitchen and am greeted by a slim figured, olive-skinned man. He wears his adorable baby blue apron, his back facing towards me as he casually stirs his Mediterranean masterpiece on the stove. “Smells great, Papá.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He turns around, the same bushy brows as David's moving higher on his face. “Sweetie, come here for a second.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hmm?” I step up next to him.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;He hands me a spoon and motions towards the pan filled with orange goodness. “Taste it for me.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I scoop up some rice, chicken, and an assortment of vegetables from the pan and allow the flavors to take hold of me. The spice, the soft rice, the chicken oozing with delicious juices—oh yes, this is it.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;While I enjoy my five seconds in heaven, I look up toward my dad and nod. “Perfect Pa—”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hey!” The croaky voice of Marco suddenly yells out. “Why is she eating the Paella before it's served? If I remember correctly, that's grounds for the Alvarez death penalty.” My dad lifts the big round pan from the stove and carries it to the dinner table. “When you go to college, you get to taste ahead of time as well, I promise.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;As if they have a sixth sense for the food being ready, my mother, David, and Violet all come around the corner at the same time. The entire family quickly finds their way into the standard seating arrangement, while Violet has a second look at my dad’s culinary accomplishment. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Yeah…” With a wrinkled nose, she shakes her head. “I’ll be skipping this Alvarez tradition. Why couldn’t you guys be like actual Hispanics and have a taco tradition or something.” &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;My dad chuckles. “You don’t know what you’re missing, Violet; this is the real Spanish taste, the taste of Valencia.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Sure,” Violet’s gaze pans over to me. “I’m going across the street to cook dinner for my mom, but I’ll be right back to make sure you don’t pack any more embarrassing stuff.” &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;It only takes a few seconds for the entire family to start greedily filling their plates. Most of us are already anticipating the fact that whatever happens, at the end of the meal, the pan will be empty. So, if we want to have our fair share, we better be quick.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;***&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;While I’m squeezed in the middle between my two brothers, I attempt to look out through the car’s windshield. I scan the horizon, hoping to catch a glimpse of the iconic Geisel Library. Obviously, this isn’t the first time driving down to the UCSD campus, but it is the most special. Because today, I’m not just visiting; today, I’m making this my new home.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I remember how all my high school classmates talked about their college plans over the last year. Some had grand ambitions of getting into some esteemed Ivy League college on the East Coast, others had their sights dead set on a specific school for a specific goal. The theater kids that NEEDED to get into Berkeley, or the geeks that view Stanford as a place of salvation. Lastly, there were those who didn't even particularly care what college they went to, as long as it was far away from home.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I don’t understand that, even the idea of moving that far away from my family scares me. That’s why I always imagined myself going to UCSD; it’s so close, I could probably stay living at home. If it wasn’t for my parents insisting I get a dorm on campus so I could learn some more ‘independence,’ I probably would have.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;While my eyes are still focused on the world outside of the car, I feel a knee poking into my right thigh. David has shifted his weight and is now taking up an unreasonable amount of space in the back seat. I try to lean into the right, reclaiming my territory, causing my brother to look up from his phone.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hey!” he says with a frown on his face. “Can you stop squeezing me into the door?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Can you stop manspreading and stabbing me with that hairy-ass leg of yours?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I’m a developing man in the prime of my life; I just require a little more space compared to you and your stick limbs.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I give him a quick jab with my elbow in response.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Ouch!” his eyes dart over to Marco in search of support. David quickly realizes he won’t be able to help him out right now, as our little brother is engrossed in his music while looking out the window on his side of the car. Switching strategies, David shifts his back to the right side of the car and grabs onto my arm. “Stop poking me!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I shake my arm in an attempt to escape his grip. “Get your paws off me!”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Hey!” My mom’s voice loudly echoes through the car. “I understand you two are afraid of missing each other, but can we please save the romping for when we are out of the car?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;In an instant, my brother and I untangle from each other and sit back straight in our seats. Presumably trying to maintain a sense of pride, David responds, “I’m not going to be missing her in the slightest. In fact, I’m already looking forward to the comfortable drive back where I won’t have to feel like a tinned sardine for a change.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;Instead of retorting with a clever response of my own, I choose to continue establishing physical supremacy by pinching him just above the knee.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Argh, Erin! Stop!” he yells out again.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“I didn’t do anything.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“Of course, you didn’t.” He rolls his eyes. “I already feel bad for your future roommate. I give her two weeks before she runs away screaming.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“They,” I say, emphasizing the pronoun. “Are going to love having me around.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“They? I thought it was a two-person dorm?”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;“It’s co-ed, you dummy.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;David chuckles. “Now I feel twice as bad for the poor fellow who ends up in your witch's cave.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:400"&gt;I was about to give him another round of the elbow jab, but my dad interjects. “I hope you’re done fighting, because we’re h